      "description": "As a supplementary confidence-building exercise, the CFD shear-stress field topology was compared against the FDA benchmark hemolysis dataset (Hariharan et al. 2011) derived from a continuous-flow ventricular-assist device (VAD) operated at 5–7 L/min and outlet pressures of 80–120 mmHg. The comparison demonstrates that the solver reproduces the characteristic high-shear blade-tip and volute-tongue regions seen in the benchmark, and the normalised shear-stress distributions show qualitative agreement (R² = 0.91 across 1 200 spatial samples). The assessment team noted that this benchmark is widely used in the literature and provides strong evidence of solver fidelity. The narrative does not address the fact that CPB circuits operate at substantially lower outlet pressures (15–40 mmHg) than VAD circuits, nor that the lower pressure differential materially alters the recirculation zone geometry and the magnitude of the peak shear-stress exposure time integral — the quantity most directly linked to the power-law hemolysis model outputs used in the primary validation result.",
